Part 5

He left on the sixth morning. The car was already loaded and idling in the driveway, with Ramanna hovering near the boot, insisting on carrying a small suitcase that Vikram was perfectly capable of lifting himself.

The Aghori was waiting by the rows of coffee plants at the edge of the yard, as if he had known the exact morning of Vikram's departure without being told. 

"Going," the Aghori said. It was not a question.

"For now," Vikram said, stopping near the low wall. "The land isn't settled yet. I will be traveling back and forth for months, maybe even longer."

"Land is never really settled," the Aghori said, sitting on the stones. "It is only borrowed for a little while. Tell me something before you go. Why this? Liquor. Why not medicine, or schools, or something that a father could be simply proud of at dinner parties?"

Vikram considered lying. He thought of the polished, corporate answers he usually gave to the board members and the politicians, but he found he didn't want to use those words here.

"It wasn't mine to choose," Vikram said, looking at the distant hills. "It was my father's business. I never wanted it—not the company, not this industry. Twice, life put me in it anyway. I am not chasing the money; I stopped believing money was the point a long time ago. I just want to finish what he started, properly, because he cannot do it anymore, and because some part of me still wants to prove I can."

"And the liquor part," the Aghori asked, his dark eyes steady. "Does that trouble you?"

"Yes," Vikram said, not softening the truth. "I know what it does to some families. I have read the same social reports that the opposition will use against our factory. I am not proud of the product. But I am proud, perhaps, of doing it honestly where I can—keeping the license clean, the taxes paid, and the workers looked after. It is not nothing. But it is also not everything."

The Aghori looked at him for a long moment. The fire-catch in his eyes from the night before was replaced now, in the clear daylight, by something much quieter. 

Then he smiled, a slow, gentle expression. He didn't explain the smile, and Vikram, who had learned by now not to ask, didn't request any explanation.

---

"Here," the Aghori said instead. 

He produced from somewhere in his ash-grey wrap a small piece of folded paper, handing it over without any ceremony. 

"Sit like this in the morning," the Aghori said. "Ten minutes, no more. And this word, repeat it when your mind runs too fast for you to catch it. It is not for the liquor board, and not for your father. It is for you, when you are alone and nobody is watching, and you still don't know who you are supposed to be that day."

Vikram unfolded the paper later, in the back of the car as they drove down the winding hill road. 

He found a simple seated posture sketched in a shaky, dark hand. Beneath the drawing, a single word was written twice, the second time heavily underlined. 

He didn't ask what the word meant. Some part of him suspected that the very act of not-asking was the real point of the gift.

Ramanna knocked on the car window as the vehicle began to move, breathless from jogging alongside it for the last few steps down the gravel path.

"Sir!" the caretaker called out, waving his hand. "Come again for the next wedding, whenever there is one in our family!"

Vikram laughed, a real, clear laugh, and promised that he would. He found—a little to his own surprise—that he meant it.

[End of Part 5]
